(16, 1, '2018-11-21 06:37:15', '2018-11-21 06:37:15', 'PRODUCTION FUNDING FOR LAKELAND NEWS IS PROVIDED BY ESSENTIA HEALTH, HERE WITH YOU, ONLINE AT ESSENTIAHEALTH.ORG; FIRST NATIONAL BANK BEMIDJI, CONTINUING THEIR SECOND CENTURY OF SERVICE TO THE COMMUNITY, A PARTNERSHIP FOR GENERATIONS, MEMBER FDIC; HOME AT HEART CARE PROVIDING PERSONAL IN-HOME CARE AND HOMEMAKING SERVICES IN NORTHERN MINNESOTA; THE MILLE LACS BAND OF OJIBWE, EMPLOYING OVER 3500 PEOPLE IN CENTRAL MINNESOTA. CELEBRATING 20 YEAR OF LOCAL NEWS IN BEMIDJI, BRAINERD AND ALL OF THE LAKE\'S COUNTRY. LAKELAND PBS IS PROUD TO PRESENT LAKELAND NEWS AT TEN. DENNIS WEIMANN WITH THE NEWS, STACY CHRISTENSON WITH THE WEATHER, AND AJ FELDMAN WITH YOUR SPORTS. &gt;&gt; DEN , EVERYONE. THANKS FOR JOINING US. A MINNESOTA ADMINISTRATIVE LAW JUDGE HAS RULED THAT A FORMER CANDIDATE FOR BEMIDJI CITY COUNCIL MUST PAY A FINE OF $500 FOR VIOLATING A MINNESOTA STATUTE THAT PROHIBITS ACCEPTING A CAMPAIGN CONTRIBUTION IN EXCESS OF $600 FROM A COMMITTEE. BEMIDJI RECENT DEBIT ROBERT SAXTON HAD FILED THE CAMPAIGN COMPLAINT AGAINST DON HEINONEN ON OCTOBER 24th UNDER THE FAIR CAMPAIGN PRACTICES ACT. ADMINISTRATIVE LAW JUDGE BARBARA J. CASE RULED ON NOVEMBER 5th THAT THERE WAS PROBABLE CAUSE IN THE CASE AND HEINONEN FILED A WRITTEN SUBMISSION ON NOVEMBER 7th IN WHICH HE ACKNOWLEDGED THE VIOLATION. THE VIOLATION REVOLVED AROUND A MINNESOTA STATUTE WHICH PROHIBITS CANDIDATES FOR OFFICE WHOSE TERRITORY HAS A POPULATION OF 100,000 OR LESS FROM ACCEPTING CONTRIBUTIONS BY AN INDIVIDUAL OR COMMITTEE IN EXCESS OF $600 IN AN ELECTION YEAR. THE CITY OF BEMIDJI HAS A POPULATION OF LESS THAN 100,000. THOMPSON RULED THAT THE DEFINITION OF COMMITTEE APPEARED TO BE BROAD ENOUGH TO INCLUDE FOUR INDIVIDUALS WHO EQUALLY DIVIDED COST OF A WEBSITE AND SOCIAL MEDIA SERVICES FOR HEINONEN\'S CAMPAIGN. HEINONEN WAS SEEKING A POSITION ON THE BEMIDJI CITY COUNCIL BUT LOST BY 35 VOTES IN THE NOVEMBER 8th ELECTION TO FORMER COUNCIL MEMBER JIM THOMPSON. &gt;&gt; DEN MIDJI\'S RAILROAD CORRIDOR PROJECT WAS NEARLY DERAILED MONDAY NIGHT DURING THE CITY COUNCIL MEETING WHEN THE CONVERSATION TURNED TO FUNDING. OUR JOSH PETERSON EXPLAINS THE POSSIBLE OPTIONS. &gt;&gt; FOR YEARS, MIDGE EMERGENCY\'S RRP CORRIDOR HAS BEEN A TOPIC OF CONVERSATION, AND NOW THE PROJECT HAS COME TO A POINT WHERE TIME IS RUNNING OUT IF THEY WISH TO MEET AN UPCOMING DEADLINE. &gt;&gt; WE\'RE AT A STAGE RIGHT NOW WHERE WE HAVE TO MAKE DECISIONS ON HOW WE WANT TO PROCEED AHEAD WITH THIS PROJECT. &gt;&gt; WHILE THE CITY HAS CONTRACTED WITH THE ST. PAUL PORT AUTHORITY TO HELP REDEVELOP THE LAND, TIME IS OF THE ESSENCE AS THERE IS A LOOMING DEADLINE FOR NECESSARY GRANTS. &gt;&gt; THIS SEEMS TO BE AN OPPORTUNITY FOR US WITH SOME ASSISTANCE TO ACTUALLY GET THIS LOCATION CLEANED UP AND, YOU KNOW, DO SOME REDEVELOPMENT. &gt;&gt; THE PHASES WOULD INCLUDE A NEEDED REVIEW OF THE LAND, WHICH WOULD COST OVER $320,000. THE CONVERSATION TURNED TO FUNDING AND HOW TO PAY FOR THE NEXT STEPS WHEN THERE\'S A CITY-WIDE INFRASTRUCTURE NEED ON THE HORIZON. &gt;&gt; I DON\'T SUPPORT THIS, BECAUSE IT\'S A 320,000-DOLLAR INCIDENT, AND IT GAVE US AN ANSWER, AND THERE WERE MORE DOLLARS TO HAVE TO BE COMMITTED. WE\'RE JUST OPENING THE DOOR. &gt;&gt; YOU\'RE LOOKING AT NUMBERS HERE THAT I CAN\'T SUPPORT FOR THE PURPOSE OF ALL THE OTHER THINGS WE HAVE GOING ON. &gt;&gt; MEANWHILE, OTHER COUNCIL MEMBERS WISH TO WAIT. &gt;&gt; MAYBE WE NEED TO THINK ABOUT WHAT NUMBER OUT THERE WOULD BE EASIER FOR SOME OF US TO SWALLOW. &gt;&gt; SO RIGHT NOW, I HAVE ABSOLUTELY PULLED MY HORNS IN 100% ON THIS. IT\'S NOT GOING TO GO AWAY AND FADE, BUT IT CERTAINLY SHOULD BE DELAYED. &gt;&gt; IN BEMIDJI, JOSH PETERSON, LAKELAND NEWS. &gt;&gt; DEN E TOPIC WAS TABLED TO PROVIDE FURTHER REVIEW OF THE PROJECT AND TO PROVIDE COUNCIL COUNSELMEMBERS WHO WERE NOT IN ATTENDANCE TO BE PART OF THE CONVERSATION. &gt;&gt; DEN MAN WHO DIED WHILE DEER HUBTING, IN AITKIN COUNTY OVER THE WEEKEND HAS BEEN IDENTIFIED AS 56-YEAR-OLD GREGORY J. NASE OF COLUMBUS. ACCORDING TO THE SHERIFF\'S OFFICE, NASE WAS HUNTING WITH HIS FAMILY ON FAMILY OWNED LAND ABOUT SIX MILES NORTHEAST OF MCGRATH. IT WAS REPORTED THAT THE FAMILY WAS HUNTING TOGETHER, MAKING A DEER DRIVE FOR A WOUNDED DEER. SHOTS WERE REPORTEDLY FIRED AT A MOVING DEER WITH SHOTS STRIKING NASE. NASE WAS PRONOUNCED DEAD AT THE SCENE. THE INCIDENT IS UNDER INVESTIGATION BY THE AITKIN COUNTY SHERIFF\'S OFFICE AND THE MINNESOTA B CRMENT A. BCA. &gt;&gt;&gt; AMERICANS ARE BEING ASKED TO NOT EAT ANY ROMAINE LETTUCE. THE REASON? THE CENTERS FOR DISEASE CONTROL AND PREVENTION SAYS IT\'S DUE TO E.COLI CONCERNS. THE CDC SAYS 32 PEOPLE IN 11 STATES HAVE BEEN INFECTED. ANOTHER 18 HAVE FALLEN ILL FROM THE SAME STRAIN IN TWO CANADIAN PROVINCES. SINCE NO COMMON GROWER, SUPPLIER, DISTRIBUTOR OR COMPANY HAS BEEN IDENTIFIED AS THE SOURCE OF THE OUTBREAK, THE CDC IS ADVISING ALL AMERICANS TO THROW OUT ANY ROMAINE LETTUCE THEY HAVE AT HOME. &gt;&gt; DEN GROUP OF BEMIDJI HIGH SCHOOL ALUMNI ARE KEEPING THE MEMORIES OF THE OLD BEMIDJI HIGH SCHOOL ALIVE WITH A NEW RESTORATION PROJECT. THE GROUP CALLED OLD BEMIDJI HIGH SCHOOL REMEMBERED REQUESTED TO HAVE A SALVAGED ARCHWAY FROM THE OLD HIGH SCHOOL RESTORED AND PLACED NEAR WHERE THE BUILDING USED TO STAND. THE ARM WOULD BE PLACED NEAR THE BEMIDJI BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB AND JW SMITH ELEMENTARY SCHOOL ON THE WEST END OF MINNESOTA AVENUE. THE BEMIDJI SCHOOL BOARD VOTED UNANIMOUSLY TO APPROVE THE LOCATION. &gt;&gt; NOW THAT THE SCHOOL BOARD HAS APPROVED OF THIS PROJECT, THE &gt;&gt; DEN LAKES AREA HABITAT FOR HUMANITY CELEBRATED THE COMPLETION OF THEIR 120th HOUSE FOR A LOCAL FAMILY IN NEED. THIS ONE WAS UNIQUE IT\'S A IT WAS A HOUSE THAT WAS IN LINE TO BE DEMOLISHED BUT WAS INSTEAD MOVED AND REFURBISHED FOR A DESERVING FAMILY. OR REPORTER RACHEL JOHNSON HAS MORE. &gt;&gt; THE HOUSE IN BAXTER WAS FILLED FROM FRONT TO BACK MONDAY WITH PEOPLE CELEBRATING A JOB WELL DONE. &gt;&gt; TODAY IS THE MOST IMPORTANT DAY FOR OU