 says transphobic violence can take forms aside from just physical being misgendered every day or being like denied like the ability to like express yourself as you you know truly are Lewis says their group wants to support transgender individuals in the end everything will be okay and you have a community and you have family here who will love and support you unconditionally even if people in your life might transgender people who need someone to talk to can call the trans lifeline I eight seven seven five six five eight eight six zero there are also several resources at Arizona State University and throughout the valley including one in ten in trance petram of Arizona Thanksgiving is just two days away and some of us may be taking time off from the gym but coming up on Cronkite news we\'re not taking any breaks as we train with FBI agents Plus learn about the efforts to preserve a historic Cemetery right here in Phoenix I\'m Judy Woodruff anchor and managing editor of the PBS Newshour the journalists of tomorrow face a fast changing media landscape but quality news remains vitally important to our communities our country and our world at asu\'s Walter Cronkite School of Journalism and mass communication students learn solid reliable reporting holding the powerful accountable and rebuilding the public\'s trust the Cronkite School and Arizona PBS preparing the next generation for a stronger future of journalism as journalists at Cronkite news we report on stories that matter to you bye the local impact we dig deeper and work tirelessly to keep you informed live in Wickenburg live in Los Angeles in Cleveland in Washington in Louisville from Jerusalem live in Philadelphia from around the world right here in Phoenix Cronkite news we report the facts and stick to the truth it\'s a little change to the law that supporters could solve a big issue for one Arizona tribe Lilly and Donahue in our Washington bureau has the latest on a bill that\'s under consideration in the Senate the Gila River federal rights of way easements and boundary clarification Act would give the Gila River Indian Community 3400 acres if it passes solving a long-standing trust issue between the United States government and the tribe every Tribal Nation has come to a point of dealing with either mismanagement or under managed record-keeping and it\'s that mismanagement of Records and Trust lands by the government that has made infrastructure planning difficult for tribal leaders in the Gila River Indian community the House bill now pending in the Senate is in response to a lawsuit filed by the tribe a decade ago to regain land and trust rights they say were encroached upon more than a century before almost 150 years later the Gila River Indian community sought resolution in the court and ultimately the Department of Interior agreed to a settlement they want to make sure sacred sites are protected by them and not outside influences and this will allow for that to occur representative Tom o\'halleran introduced the bill and says it\'s just one part of a larger effort to right wrongs that have lingered in Indian country for too long it\'s a never-ending process right now and it\'s not been I think the Congress has not done this job over the last number of decades the Gila River Indian community is located south of the valley stretching from Goodyear to past Queen Creek councilman Barney Ennis jr. says that the tribe wants to be good neighbors to Phoenix while also restoring rights to their people and one of her 1 preserve but also to ensure that the the folks affected by this not become victims of dispute in Washington Lillian Donohue Cronkite news the bill would prohibit gaming on the affected land but while the bill has already passed the house time is running out in the Senate which is only scheduled to be in session for three more weeks for decades a piece of land on Phoenix\'s Southside has hid the secrets of hundreds of early Latino settlers who helped build the city many of them buried in a place that seems long-forgotten Cronkite news reporter Brittany Watson talked with activists and community members who are speaking out in hoping this piece of the city\'s history gets the recognition it deserves vandalized trashed abandoned this unmarked field is the final resting place for over 300 Mexican pioneers who spent their lives helping build Phoenix in its early days this nondescript patch of land located off 12th Street in Broadway is actually the Sotelo heard cemetery with its earliest recorded burial dating back to the late 1800s Phoenix wouldn\'t be what it is today if it wasn\'t for those people who were the foundation of the City of Phoenix and and somehow we forget that many residents who live near Sotelo her don\'t even know their homes are just yards away from a cemetery a place where many children were also buried some of those who do know say they\'ve seen this final resting place get trashed it often see people writing their motorbikes and running across the field throwing rocks and messing around I don\'t think they had an idea of being a cemetery the Pioneer Cemetery Association has worked to preserve historic cemeteries like Sotelo herd by salvaging and removing what they can of the damaged headstones to try and preserve what little is left Litchfield Park resident Ellie Roman has spent years researching her ancestors eventually finding out that eight of them were buried at Sotelo heard a cemetery that she had never even heard of before I was really really surprised we had so many family members there but it made sense they were ranchers laborers they worked the herd ranch my different branches of the fan they\'ve all been here it seems like from the early 1900\'s but a lot has changed since that time currently the cemetery is enclosed on two sides leaving the other two sides exposed representatives from the nonprofit organization that own this land say that they do not have the money to finish all the improvements that are still needed the nonprofit organization trellis owns the land where the cemetery sits they were supposed to build low-income housing on part of the property but that clearly hasn\'t happened unfortunately the market crashed and to this day we haven\'t built anything but we have just maintained the land the Pioneer Cemetery Association in trellis have proposed improvements including building an iron fence along the south and west perimeters having a monument in adding an entrance to the cemetery on 12th Street the repairs will cost thousands of dollars the main question now is where will that money come from we need everyone\'s help to raise the funding to finish this beautification project for sabelo Hurd cemetery to know that their babies or family members are there not to have that respect is just heartbreaking in Phoenix Brittany Watson Cronkite news representatives from both trellis and the Pioneer Cemetery Association say they have plans to speak with the Phoenix City Council about taking ownership of the land and maintaining the cemetery there\'s still no set date on when that meeting will take place the California condor faced extinction as recently as two decades ago but coming up on Cronkite news find out how the species is making a comeback holiday season is finally upon us and we are seeing those cooler temperatures on the top half in the southwest region current temperatures coming up next on Cronkite news [Music] [Music] [Music] [Applause] [Music] recovery efforts are still ongoing in California as forest fires continue to burn across the state the California Department of Forestry and Fire Protection said the campfire in Northern California is now 70% contained and more help could be on the way rain is expected in the area later this week which could help the ongoing fight however officials warn that this could lead to flash flooding and mudslides earlier this fall for California condors were released by the Peregrine fund at Vermilion Cliffs National Monument next month more condors will be released in California Cronkite news reporter Emily 4 explains these releases are part of an ongoing effort to bring the condors back from the brink of extinction I just ended up kind of falling in love with it nadia co faith conservation and science associate for the santa barbara zoo is reminiscing about California condors seal faith works to understand condors and their nesting habits by 1987 all 22 condors left in the wild were taken into captive breeding an attempt to save them from extinction it\'s not only a fascinating species but it\'s been a fascinating program to work with through the US Fish and Wildlife Service and other organizations like the Ventana Wildlife Society California condors have since been reintroduced into the wild and their population is slowly growing in fact this year is really exciting because this year we had a record number of nests in Southern California there was 12 that\'s the most of any that we would we know historically yet condors are still battling they\'re leading cause of death lead poisoning condors are scavengers and eat the remains of animals killed by hunters the only issue is that led ammunition fragments into many many many tiny pieces inside a carcass rachael Wolstenholme manages the Condor program at pinnacles National Park she says she doesn\'t want to discourage hunting but she wants to offer alternatives to lead ammunition there\'s copper bismuth rifle ammunition there\'s also steel shot if people are using lead shot right now like in a shotgun they\'re still shot but Wolstenholme is hopeful California condors will be taken off the endangered species list in the near future I\'ve seen six or seven flying just over the high peaks there I like to say less than a decade I actually know we could get there sooner it\'s all about making sure that they have a clean food resource there are currently 44 California condors managed by pinnacles National Park in December three more will be released from this site we do what\'s called a soft release and so what we do will open the trap door so they can leave when they\'re ready joint efforts and successful releases keep wolfson home and seal faith motivated it\'s just been so clobbered have been it\'s so great to see so many people you know wanting this bird to succeed and I think that\'s just been really special to be a part of in Los Angeles Emily for Cronkite news there are five Condor release sites in North America one of them right here at the Vermillion cliffs in Arizona condors can also be seen at the Grand Canyon Horseshoe Bend is not only one of the most scenic spots in Arizona it\'s also one of the most popular leading to huge problems with parking a National Park Service plan to expand parking is now under way but the city of Page has had to close the north parking lot for construction and place other restrictions until the project is complete in March but for now tour buses with more than 20 passengers won\'t be able to park on site and people will be prohibited from parking along u.s. 89 it\'s Thanksgiving week here in Phoenix that\'s right let\'s go to Alexis and the Weather Center to see how the weather will be for this holiday alexis good afternoon everyone it is finally Thanksgiving week and we are feeling those cooler temperatures here in the valley 78 degrees right now here in Phoenix sitting at dew point about 22 degrees and for the next eight hours we will be dipping our toes into the 60s at about 68 degrees at 7 p.m. going all the way down as 60 degrees at o\'clock later tonight looking at the height on the state tomorrow gonna be topping off here in Phoenix at about 75 degrees up north and Flagstaff 55 degrees 67 in Globe and 76 degrees in Yuma the big question is is what can we expect for Thanksgiving we\'ll go ahead and pull out those light jackets because we\'re gonna be topping off about 71 degrees and it is gonna be mostly cloudy outside but speaking of Thanksgiving we have a lot of family events going on later this weekend as you can see we have the city scape going on the 23rd a p.m. it\'s gonna be 65 degrees go ahead and bundle up because we\'re gonna stay in the 60s for the Phoenix Zoo Scott\'s dazzle and Mesa Lights at 63 degrees the 23rd as we look into the seven-day forecast we are gonna have a couple cloudy days out there but as we dive into the weekend we are seeing nothing but sunshine on Saturday it\'s gonna be 70 degrees ending my week on Tuesday at 68 degrees from the Cronkite weather Center I\'m Alexis Leal Cronkite news do you think you have the skills to be an FBI agent coming up on Cronkite news find out what it takes to join their team of skilled professionals next if you\'re looking for one show that tells you what happened that day in the world of business it\'s NVR we saw a classic shipwreck Nordstrom this opening stores will digit day and crude climb we\'re there to help our audience find new investment ideas market still dad\'s room to go up nightly Business Report is the longest-running business television program in history weeknights at on Arizona PBS I met Barry ESPN SportsCenter anchor and grads would\'ve asu\'s Walter Cronkite School of Journalism and mass communication with its bachelor\'s and master\'s degrees in sports journalism the Cronkite School is preparing the next generation of sports journalists to tell stories that matter stories that excite inspire and inform Cronkite immerses students in covering sports at all levels in one of the country\'s top sports markets it\'s this hands-on experience under the guidance of award-winning sports media veterans that shape the top journalists of tomorrow VI is looking to hire 900 new special agents everyone is encouraged to apply but as our reporter Anthony toll tree found out there are some requirements you\'ve gotta meet the FBI fit test for events 12 points required to pass improve you meet the physical standards to make it as an FBI agent this test was designed to push that and lets you know that yes physically you can handle this you can handle the firearms aspect of it you could handle the defensive tactics aspect of it if you do engage with a perpetrator of some sort of a subject that\'s you\'re after this test for the person who stays in shape and takes care of themselves should not be difficult I go to the gym a few days a week so I figured how hard could it be well the test starts off with 60 seconds of sit-ups slow harder than journalism at 47 in a minute earned me four points next up the 300 meter run a time of forty eight point two seconds added another three points to my total halfway done seven points Supervisory Special Agent as Elle Grigsby says there is one simple key to passing the test train this is this is one portion of the process that you have the answers to the test back to my exam for push-ups similar to the first event the goal is to do as many as possible but in this part of the test there is no time limit just do as many as you can till you can\'t go up anymore way less than I thought only got one point for my 32 FBI approved push-ups putting me at eight points heading into the final step not too far off from jumping from journalists to Special Agent then came the mile and a half run look use that break now with only five minutes rest in between each event I definitely felt the toll of the test so how did i do on the run I lost after dropping two points I ended with a final score of six it looks like I\'m sticking a journalism after all in Phoenix Anthony Torre Cronkite news if you have any interest in looking to become an FBI agent the FBI developed the FBI fit test app to help people get accustomed to the test the app will count your push-ups sit-ups and give you your time to rest that\'s it for Cronkite news tonight thanks for joining us for top arizona stories any time go to cronkitenews.azpbs.org [Music] [Music] support for Arizona PBS comes from viewers like you and from SUV right yes well we not only fixed events but we added a few things built in 4G LTE Wi-Fi apple carplay compatibility at a seven-inch diagonal touchscreen we also painted it whoa it\'s a Chevy this is the Chevy equal [Music] after Charlottesville is your sense that there\'s new energy joining these movements this promo Southers is my clip frontline and ProPublica investigates there\'s video of you launching yourself into that crowd tonight a on Arizona PBS explore new ideas and new worlds here on Arizona PBS a community service of error', 'Cronkite News presents in-depth reporting on border issues, sustainability, education, politics, health, business and justice in Phoenix and across Arizona.', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cronkite-news-presents-in-depth-reporting-on-border-issues-sustainability-education-politics-health-business-and-justice-in-phoenix-and-across-arizona', '', '', '2018-11-21 06:47:48', '2018-11-21 06:47:48', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=25', 0, 'post', '', 0),
