(27, 1, '2018-11-21 06:47:48', '2018-11-21 06:47:48', 'travel to Hawaii with ankle burn huh burden in concert Saturday a on Arizona PBS Phoenix this is Cronkite news a federal judge in California blocked president Trump\'s Asylum ban what this means for the thousands of migrants seeking asylum from their home countries in Central America plus the California condor face the possibility of extinction years ago will track the efforts that are now boosting their population and do you think you\'ve got what it takes to be an FBI agent we take you on a behind-the-scenes look at how these agents apply for duty next Cronkite news starts now [Music] good evening and welcome to Cronkite news on Arizona PBS i\'m jordan daftness and i\'m matt lively thank you for joining us tonight the White House and federal agencies are fighting back in the latest border battle last night a federal judge ordered a temporary block on the Trump administration\'s plan to deny asylum to migrants crossing the southern border thousands of migrants have already arrived at the border in her stayin in Tijuana President Trump issued a rule blocking their right to apply for asylum earlier this month Judge John s.tiger from US District Court in California handed down the ruling saying that president Trump\'s Proclamation conflicts with immigration law in the expressed intent of Congress spokespeople from the Department of Justice and the Department of Homeland Security released a joint statement saying in part our Asylum system is broken and it is being abused by tens of thousands of meritless claims every year as the Supreme Court affirmed this summer Congress has given the president broad authority to limit or even stop the entry of aliens into this country the restraining order will remain in effect until December 19th when the judge has scheduled another hearing members of the Phoenix community who help many of these migrants once they reached the United States say they are often misunderstood the first church UCC has worked with both Immigration and Customs Enforcement and the Phoenix restoration program providing food and temporary shelter to hundreds of migrants after they\'ve applied for asylum in the u.s. Senior Pastor James Pennington says he\'s had a hard time understanding some of the decisions made by President Trump when it comes to immigration policy I think these immigrants and these refugees would be really contributing to our culture and to our society and I really think it\'s important to consider that so if it does if he does and is allowed to because supposedly he can make those decisions and those edicts I just think it\'s that healthy for our country because we can\'t you know we just can\'t close our doors and our hearts to people that are seeking a better life according to Minister Pennington the number of immigrants being released into their care by ice has gone up considerably in the last few weeks First Church UCC also had the designation of a sanctuary church for some time even before today\'s Asylum policy debate hundreds of migrants from the caravan have already arrived near port of entry in southern Arizona Douglas mayor Robert your I told kvo a that two busloads of Honduran migrants are now staying in shelters and private homes just across the border and Agua Prieta a Mexican official said some other buses from the caravan were turned back because aqua Prieta could not handle the influx of people President Trump might also give new authority to military troops who protect the border personnel in federal property it would allow the nearly 6,000 troops at the border to intervene and protect migrants if they engage in violence Airbnb has been a provider of living spaces for people looking for a place to rest their heads now the company is opening its doors to refugees here in Phoenix reporter cami Clark explains Airbnb s open homes program this house looks no different than any other here in Phoenix but this house is used to help house refugees through the Airbnb program open homes which has several partners including hospitality Services Center and the International Rescue Committee when IRC called and said Aaron B&amp;B; was asking if we would be able to cooperate with them we felt like that was a really good match the refugees stay in the home for about one to two weeks for free it\'s just part of the services the IRC offers here in Phoenix we help resettle refugees from around the world when they first arrived in Phoenix we help them find housing employment healthcare education as of September 2018 Airbnb has been able to house more than 15,000 people through open homes according to their website during the winter time it can be harder to house refugees here in Phoenix Airbnb is making an effort to get more hosts cheering from someone you trust about something like this is so so impactful and so we\'re trying to spread the word person by person neighborhood by neighborhood because we know there\'s a huge interest in Phoenix in helping so there may be some uncertainty about who is coming into your home the safety of open homes help refugees many from the war-torn Congo settle into new lives they\'re fleeing violence and they\'re looking for a safe place to land so I think that\'s probably the biggest hurdle to get over is in people\'s minds who the refugees are and is it safe to have them in my home Airbnb is looking to expand their open homes program to include other causes in glendale cami Clark Cronkite news in 2017 Airbnb had pledged four million dollars to the International Rescue Committee to help aid critical global populations over to the for years according to the Airbnb website Arizona Governor Doug Ducey met with Senator elect Kyrsten Sinema today Ducey tweeted out that he in cinema had a productive meeting about issues they can work on together including Arizona\'s water future CNN is reporting that Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell is lobbying governor Ducey to choose martha mcsalley to replace john kyle in the Senate should he leave before his term ends in 2020 mcsalley a two-term representative lost her senate bid to cinema two weeks ago the Arizona Supreme Court justices elected justice Robert and Brundle as the next Chief Justice in justice an a Scott Timmer to serve as vice chief justice Brett Anil is a former Yavapai County Superior Court judge and Timur is a former state court of appeals judge both justices will serve five-year terms in July first today on transgender Day of Remembrance the rainbow community on the Arizona State University campus hosted a visual remembrance there honoring the 22 transgender people killed worldwide this year according to the Human Rights Campaign reporter Hollie Bernstein takes us to the event and shows us resources available for those who might need it trans Day of Remembrance it\'s usually a very solemn day because we\'re remembering the the impact that stigma and transphobia has on our community still Michael Lewis is at Hayden lawn representing trans fam a club focused on helping transgender students find community and access to resources they identify as non-binary it\'s not cosmetic it\'s not a choice it\'s something we\'re born as and we just want to live today Hayden lawn visual displays remember those who have lost their lives this year due to transphobic violence which is violence that relates to a person\'s gender identity according to gayatri Gary Rajan the director of community coordination for the rainbow coalition at ASU there are a lot of ways violence can be inflicted upon people who identify as transgender a lot of transgender people like experience in intimate partner violence there\'s a lot of just like street violence there\'s a lot of violence due to the professions that trans people often trans women of color are forced to kind of be a part of because of the criminalization of those of their like identities and lack of like access to jobs because of discrimination diri Rajan says transphobic violence can take forms aside from just physical being misgendered every day or being like denied like the ability to like express yourself as you you know truly are Lewis says their group wants to support transgender individuals in the end everything will be okay and you have a community and you have family here who will love and support you unconditionally even if people in your life might transgender people who need someone to talk to can call the trans lifeline I eight seven seven five six five eight eight six zero there are also several resources at Arizona State University and throughout the valley including one in ten in trance petram of Arizona Thanksgiving is just two days away and some of us may be taking time off from the gym but coming up on Cronkite news we\'re not taking any breaks as we train with FBI agents Plus learn about the efforts to preserve a historic Cemetery right here in Phoenix I\'m Judy Woodruff anchor and managing editor of the PBS Newshour the journalists of tomorrow face a fast changing media landscape but quality news remains vitally important to our communities our country and our world at asu\'s Walter Cronkite School of Journalism and mass communication students learn solid reliable reporting holding the powerful accountable and rebuilding the public\'s trust the Cronkite School and Arizona PBS preparing the next generation for a stronger future of journalism as journalists at Cronkite news we report on stories that matter to you bye the local impact we dig deeper and work tirelessly to keep you informed live in Wickenburg live in Los Angeles in Cleveland in Washington in Louisville from Jerusalem live in Philadelphia from around the world right here in Phoenix Cronkite news we report the facts and stick to the truth it\'s a little change to the law that supporters could solve a big issue for one Arizona tribe Lilly and Donahue in our Washington bureau has the latest on a bill that\'s under consideration in the Se