s know what changes they want to see in Environmental Policy to me when when we don\'t care for the environment when we don\'t address climate change that is that\'s not fair to future generations and so I think their voices really need to be heard here at the legislature because it\'s about their future the students are hopeful that the more they voice their concerns the more changes will be made in Phoenix Ashley Holcomb Cronkite news ASU is one of many universities paving the way in finding new solutions to providing natural energy-efficient resources to students on campus as well as maintaining a clean environment Cronkite news reporter Chantal de la joya takes us to UCLA where sustainable technology is giving students the opportunity to spend more productive time outdoors honestly I didn\'t even know that we had them but I think it\'s a great idea she\'s talking about new solar-powered umbrellas which are making it convenient for students to study outside without wearing their mobile devices are about to die we figured not only was it a great way to make sustainable technology visible for students but it\'s also a really great way to encourage students to spend more time outdoors with funding from the University of California\'s green initiative fund Sophie and her group were able to install five umbrellas popular kerckhoffs patio there\'s between three and ten dollars taken out of every single students tuition and that goes into the green initiative fund and then students across campus can apply to receive funding from from the green initiative fund for different sustainable and conservation projects on campus the umbrellas can hold a charge for up to eight hours without sunlight which is great for students to be able to study outdoors I think they\'re really useful it was nice to come out here and still be able to charge my phone also students in shades before we didn\'t used to have these it would be like burning Sun and while these students will graduate and move on University staff predict we\'ll be around to see more of these projects in years ahead I mean I think it\'s very satisfying you need power you device the sun\'s right there cut all the middle middle people out and you just power your device directly and at $2,500 per umbrella these solar advocates say it\'s money well spent in Los Angeles Chantal del Aguila Cronkite news ASU currently has installed ten ngr solar panel devices across all campuses the collaborations with light works has been providing energy efficient solutions for faculty staff and students the City of Phoenix is currently recycling approximately 17,000 pounds a year of glass not all blasts gets recycled reporter Nicole Gutierrez tells us how one company bases its business on old bottles according to the EPA people in the u.s. generated more than 11 million tons of class and 2014 alone and only one-fourth of that glass is recycled but a valley company is rescuing wine bottles to do its part in recycling process this was a perfectly good wine bottle now it\'s on its way to a new life is an example of a glass that might be made from a bottle like this Fredo Amaro is owner of refreshed glass he refreshes old wine bottles into cocktail and water glasses his business has processed more than 1 million bottles in eight years this is a craft we have the ability to do printing and custom engraving as well and then we also make planters some people use these as as shot glasses so we have a fairly wide variety of different functional uses that we can make out of a single wine bottle Meghan circles whether using cups we know the recycled wine bottles is both functional and durable for their restaurants working bars my whole life and on average I\'d say probably a dozen glasses get broke in a week and I probably on the lighter ends whereas these maybe a dozen every couple months McGregor also has classes made specifically for his bar so I like the fact that they\'re all different sides of a slightly different color or something a little bit different about it so these are all the tops of the wine bottles as you can tell so I made these surfboards in my garage and these are a whiskey flight so now if you don\'t want to get just you know one file of whiskey you can take four different kinds and get a sample of all four whiskey\'s according to keep Phoenix beautiful you can do your parts and recycles last by making sure bottles and jars as well as food grade glass containers make it to the recycling bin in the first place remember window panes mirrors light bulbs and treated glass like the ones you find in your car should be disposed elsewhere and the broadcast liner Nicole Kyra\'s Cronkite news water in the Verde River is under a lot of stress from farmers in the Verde Valley I spent the day with one farmer looking to conserve with the help of a group that has restored over 2 million gallons of water farming is Mike I mean my calling my purpose Zach Houser its purpose was also the family business covering six hundred acres of the Verde Valley in northern Arizona as far as farming goes were the largest in the valley I made your component of farming water the Verde River looks abundant now but not for long water in the Verde Valley is not adjudicated meaning it\'s not regulated we can use you know whatever we want and but you know us being responsible we like to use as little as possible through flood irrigation this carrot field here would be flooded for hours with gallons of water starting from this end and ending with that end but the problem is those plants where we started will be in water for hours and these plants are dry but drip irrigation can fix that we\'re somewhere in the neighborhood of 50 percent efficient with flood where as drip can get in the 90% range efficient converting to drip cost a thousand dollars per acre a price that some farmers are not able to pay according to Kim Sonic from the Nature Conservancy you have to install a pump you have to have filtered water you have a power cost associated with the farmer takes on and you have a lot of upfront labor to get that equipment in the ground the nature conservancy funds projects throughout the Verde Valley with the help of changed the course a nationwide campaign to restore fresh water change the course purchase companies like REI and coca-cola to offset their water usage by funding projects and build a concentrate see the actual impact in an area that is iconic beautiful a great place to paddle and connected to the health of the watershed now that the project is paid for it\'s up to the Hauser\'s to make it work trying to carry on you know tradition not mess up the name too much beyond the Verde Valley changed the course of projects across ten states in Mexico the spring season is officially here trees are blooming which means the bees are hard at work a local beekeeper sheeps ships his hives off to California where his bees are used to pollinate almond orchards our Cronkite news reporter Adriana de alva followed the bees to find out why they\'re doing so important work this time of year a synchronized hum signaled honey bees are hard at work in Chowchilla California the small town just north of Fresno is home to almond orchards the trees need the bees to pollinate flowers the bees work begins here when the flower blooms and it ends when an almond is produced this year beekeeper Vicente Gonzales ships his colonies from Arizona to California and the demand continues to grow more than 2 million bee colonies are needed to cover 1 million acres of these all in trees in California they come from all corners of the country and roughly 5,700 of them come from the center in the Union these are critical for not just almonds these are utilized in a lot of pollination of tree fruits other vegetable crops bee brokers like Ryan cousins connect bee colonies with the farmers that need them so Tom Wilkinson assembiy n I\'m trying to keep them healthy so when they come to this paradise of flowers they take advantage and I\'ll do what they need to do which is to produce for us this hard-working Bunch serves a great purpose to build their hives and help us survive their short lives we\'ll only last an average of 40 days in the spring so next spring a new buzz will fill the air of these orchards in Chowchilla California Adriana de alva Cronkite news here in Arizona after years of drought the Salt River should be flowing this year bringing in lots of raptors and their money reporter connect ja fills us in from the canyon I\'m here at the bottom of the Salt River Canyon where the Salt River flows to the state of Arizona and if you listen closely you can hear the rapids behind me thousands of tourists come out to go rafting every year and this season the water levels are considered exceptional tour guides from Colorado pack their bags and set up camp in the Salt River Canyon from February to May this year they expect to host thousands of tourists from all over the world I had some people from New Brunswick Canada I\'ve taken people down from India sometimes there\'s Chinese tourists that come through it\'s one of those things that attracts people from all over the world if you\'re a river enthusiast and you hear the salt rivers running they come Grady has been rafting these Rapids since 2013 at that time the river was flowing at about 500 cubic feet per second today it has reached 18,000 cubic feet per second the increase in water flow is due to the snow caps melting in the White Mountains the last time we had this kind of a Spring was probably in 2010 so seven years ago so it doesn\'t happen very often but get out and visit the State Parks rafting veteran Joe Greiner says Arizona wilderness as an experienced tourists and locals should not miss your heart\'s racing because there\'s people coming potentially coming in behind you you know you what you get loaded up again paddle out into the load water fall off my jacket you know death all you know that day when we discovered that the wilderness trip was now accessible to everyone was pretty tight while it is accessible you either need to go with a guide or get a permit to raft by yourself in the Salt River Canyon kanessa Cronkite news with wildfire season quickly approaching over 30 local state and federal fire agencies participated in wildland response training reporter Morgan wheeler spent the day learning just how these fire heroes prepare Arizona is known for hot dry and windy summers the perfect condition for wildfires one of the situations that really stick with me is down the monument fire which was outside of Sierra Vista come on to the first day one of the first engines actually responded 2015 millions of acres have burned across Arizona making it especially important for a community to prepare themselves for wildfire season 30 state and federal fire agencies participated in two days of intense wildland fire training several different stations where they go through a mock scenario that ends with a practice deployment when we were teaching was firing and holding technique so it\'s literally where the the term fight fire with fire comes from we use fire to suppress other fires and with them being structure firefighters they don\'t get the hands-on of getting to light the fires and see the fire interactions and put it into play nearly as often as we do hiding wildfires is different for individual firefighters adrenaline rush your I mean the flames are right there either I mean it\'s right here in funny or it\'s far away but I mean you\'re you\'re just you\'re huffing forty five pounds plus maybe some days it\'s just a lot of endurance and hard work all day long as drills come to a close and wildfires become closer firefighters need to be ready at all times pre-planning you prepare for that before the season so it doesn\'t befit you know eating right drinking lots of water you know well ahead of time and just being ready for that call come any minute most wildfires are caught early by firefighters but there\'s no way in predicting where or when the next large fire will spark in phoenix morgan wheeler Cronkite news eco friendly businesses are popping up in the valley but one in particular has been leading the way for years Cronkite news reporter Emma Lockhart took a look at a local restaurant that\'s reducing their carbon footprints in unique ways from massive solar panel structures to insulation made out of blue gene/l Charro a restaurant in Paradise Valley is taking sustainability to the next level we weren\'t driven by returns it was more the responsibility to the planet Christy Moore an operating partner at El Charro strives to run the business as environmentally conscious as possible they have a macerator to reduce waste solar powered energy charging stations for electric cars in on-site well for water and locally and organically grown food we looked under every rock of what we can do better and we continue to strive to meet that goal and to tender customers in an environmentally conscious customer base that\'s growing in Arizona it\'s going to become more of a demand of customers and that\'s why I think you see the spread so much of it now is that there\'s more people that have had that great experience and now they\'re expecting it and so restaurants have to follow George fennel a customer al charm sees the trend I have noticed over the last five or 10 years that you see more of this in restaurants it hasn\'t it hasn\'t hit I think as big as I\'d like to see it but it\'s certainly out there more hope the sustainability culture at El Charro inspires others and helped shift the restaurant industry in a greener direction in Paradise Valley and a la carte Cronkite news jarl was the first restaurant to get LEED Gold certified in Arizona thanks for joining us for the special edition of Cronkite news for more multimedia coverage go to cronkitenews.azpbs.org and click on the sustainability tab', 'Sustainability beat bring you stories of Arizona water conservation, recycling efforts, energy innovations, and new initiatives to protect the environment.', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '41-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-11-21 07:11:18', '2018-11-21 07:11:18', '', 41, 'http://localhost/wordpress/43/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
