(44, 1, '2018-11-21 07:12:44', '2018-11-21 07:12:44', 'Phoenix this is Cronkite news hello and welcome to this special edition of Cronkite news I\'m Chloe Nordquist thanks for joining us one of our Cronkite news reporting teams takes a special focus on sustainability and the environment tonight I look back at some of their top stories of the year all this month you and your family can learn how to be more green today members of ASU school of sustainability we\'re at the Arizona Science Center for the third annual family day as william simpson reports with some simple steps you can help save the planet what does it mean to be involved in sustainability and then what can they do impact was the main goal at the sustainability solutions festival at the Arizona Science Center today always comes down at the end what choices do I make what choices do you make what choices do with people the community make but the idea of doing things at the individual level applies all over the planet students like Nicholas represented asu\'s Walton sustainable award at the Arizona region future city competition at the Arizona Science Festival they were able to share their projects and spectators we chose it because the theme this year\'s waste management system so we had to come up with an innovative way to create a waste management system that not producing it that was green and efficient and maybe these young scientists and engineers will have the next big idea to make our world more sustainable in phoenixville in some sense the sustainability solutions festival would continue throughout the next two weeks for residents to get involved at different Valley events the next event will be thursday at the asu tempe campus with a focus on global environmental change and urbanization arizona mcdonald\'s has brewed up a new program to reduce their waste by thirty pounds each day and help local schools Elena Mendoza tells us more about their newest recycling initiative gets it hyperness caffeine so it can bounce up and grow kids in coffee normally don\'t go hand-in-hand but at Madison Simas elementary school it\'s a key part of the curriculum by coming out to the garden because I like helping the plant seeing how they sprout digs which stands for discovery is growing gardens at Simas has been a hands-on science based gardening program at the school for 17 years with the help of McDonald\'s the school doesn\'t have to pay for or struggle to find coffee grounds for their gardens any longer mccafe gardens grow up program is amazing for us because we\'ve in the past had to hunt down where we\'re going to get our coffee grounds from Madison thymus is one of 130 schools across the state that is partnered with McDonald\'s to recycle their used coffee grounds Arizona schools participating in the mccafe school gardens grow program expected over thousands of pounds of waste from going into the waste stream nationally McDonald\'s has a good neighbor good grounds program Arizona restaurants are the first to partner with the Department of Education the average McDonald\'s produces 30 pounds of coffee grounds every day 11,000 pounds of coffee grounds a year and how can we keep that out of the landfills well we can give it to the schools it\'s a win-win situation it\'s beneficial to the environment and it makes learning fun for the students and just learning about what how we plant in Phoenix Elena Mendoza Cronkite news McDonald\'s plants begin a similar program later this year so customers can get used to the grounds for their gardens to tree climbing enthusiasts are headed to the tonto national forest on saturday for arizona\'s annual tree climbing competition Cronkite news reporter Ben Margit went to the event to learn more about this unique sport a few of the tree climbers on Saturday told me that they love tree climbing and they I believe them because it\'s no easy task even ones as small as this one difficult to get up in most people probably don\'t have this in mind when they hear about tree climbers they\'re gonna think we\'re weird tree huggers or something like that but no I mean we\'re athletes tree trimmers from across the state competed at the boys Thompson Arboretum Saturday for the chance to be called Arizona\'s top tree climber it culminated in the Masters challenge a true test of all the skills they would normally use in their day jobs we\'re not cutting or doing any harm to the trees it\'s non-invasive tree climbing to mimic what we do on the job every day three competitors made it to the Masters challenge but it was Andy young the reigning champion owner of the tree amigos that took home the title for a second year in a row he chalks it up to his very early start from a young age I was climbing door jambs climbing the refrigerator I\'d climb anything i could not knowing that i\'m in wiping my occupation when I got older and that\'s what this whole competition was all about refining their skills in a competitive environment with the end goal of doing their day jobs better and safer coming out here and learning this and doing this in practicing for it keeps me you know adept at my job and safe at my job every day it\'s the main reason we come out here main reason I come out here we come oh man all day next up for Andy is the western chapter tree climbing championship held in Santa Barbara in late March live at encanto park ben maher shot Cronkite news the waste management open tees off this week but the grass isn\'t the only thing that\'s green on the course Cronkite news reporter Lillian Simpson discovered what waste management is doing the save and recycle water used at the event so if you think about where we have this all tournament we are on a desert so just knowing that we can make a little impact to help you know restore water to those critical water sources but something we\'re very proud of one of the goals of the waste management Phoenix Open keep the Greens green waste management teamed up with change the course and says it plans to put all the water used during the tournament back into the Colorado River Basin Verde River Arizona resident Sarah wood wasn\'t surprised by the sustainability movement I knew this was kind of all about the recycling that kind of event so I seen element little bands being put up in think it\'s a good thing you\'ll only see recycle and compost bins at the tournament no trash a lab how can we sort of preserve this beautiful environment and so that\'s what we looked at is you know zero weight so let\'s let\'s figure out how we can make it the greenest tournament it can be in addition to those bins you can win prizes by knowing what goes in which bent in Scottsdale Lillian Simpson Cronkite news a new dam is being built for tempe town lake to replace the current rubber dam that has caused issues in the past when it\'s completed it will be the largest hydraulically operated steel gate dam system in the country Cronkite news reporter Kendall Bartley is live at tempe town lake to tell you about this 47 million dollar project water in tempe town lake is glistening from the hot Arizona Sun but it won\'t be that way for long once the water is removed it will take another couple weeks to remove the old dam it\'s going to be used in irrigation for your yard for a park there\'s lots of ways that this water is going to be reused it\'s a it\'s a tremendous resource and we realize that water is precious the goal is to have the project completed and damn reopened with SRP canal water by April thirtieth in the meantime the life beneath the lake surface has a place to go we have been working since fall to ask anglers to take as many of these fish as they can and take them out of the lake by catching them we have not stocked any of our sport fish we have not stocked any fish since early you know earlier this year one Tempe resident hopes this new dam is worth it the only thing I\'m really concerned about is that there\'s a lot of money it\'s gone into building these new floodgates and it\'s a kind of a revolutionary thing that they\'re doing I just hope it works city officials say they did research to find the right damn for the job there were 20 different technologies that we looked at and evaluated and this one was by far the best Tempe leaders warned no one should enter the lake bed after the water is removed because it\'s unsafe it\'s like quicksand live in tempe I\'m Kendall Bartley Cronkite news leave only footprints and take only pictures isn\'t just an old adage in Arizona it\'s the law reporter Lillian Simpson traveled to Lost Dutchman State Park and found one couple not following the rules Lost Dutchman is one of many state parks protected by the state of Arizona visitors are asked to leave the park empty-handed but this canadian couple can\'t seem to help themselves from taking a piece of the park with them you can pin the word if you like it you can put love hill\'s Nicole and Roger have traveled from Texas to California and now to Arizona adding rocks to their painted collection she chose the rock and it up okay I could ping something with that we try to tell people when they come in what the rules are and also we give out brochures with a map and it has regulations on it basically people aren\'t supposed to remove rocks or objects that they find on the trails even though Park Rangers do their best to preserve Arizona State Parks some hikers and campers don\'t see the harm in taking a little piece of Arizona before they go nicey a rock yes I said I told the tumor and my friends he dad ugh hey she\'s really it\'s like a diet see the tears and the nose and the hives everyone took one Rockwell pretty soon there wouldn\'t be many rocks left so we asset they just leave everything in places they find it this couple says taking the rocks help them remember the beauty of Arizona when the Sun Goes Down Under rugged about you sofas a beautiful music 15 the park rangers say leaving the rocks where nature put them is even more beautiful in Apache Junction Lillian Simpson Cronkite news in Arizona it is illegal to remove anything from our state parks but the amount of the fine is determined by the judge every single day around 4,000 children die from getting sick from unsafe drinking water Cronkite news reporter Ben Marja tells us how a Scottsdale nonprofit is involving children in its efforts to bring clean water to the less fortunate most kids at the Phoenix Children\'s Museum knew what they were coloring this morning a drop of water but only the older ones could grasp why some people aren\'t getting good water and we\'re trying to build them a water tower to get fresh clean water it\'s part of the planet water foundations efforts to bring clean drinking water to people in third world countries something most of us take for granted you turn on the faucet and you don\'t even think about it or where you go out to water your lawn you don\'t even think about it in educating and involving young children as part of planet waters campaign to bring more awareness to water problems impoverished countries face it helps them stay in school get better grades and have an opportunity to kind of move beyond where they are today it\'s a game-changer for the entire community and for the kids the drawings will be sent to children in Cambodia to a town where the foundation is currently building a clean water system we\'re going to send the messages to other children far far away over whole other country and it gave the kids a chance to really kind of connect water is the one thing that binds us all together is kind of you know world citizens you know what those kids are gonna really appreciate this alright and they\'re going to try and send a message back to you also to see the town in Cambodia received the clean water system and the drawings from children here in Phoenix tuned to the World Water Day special on Arizona PBS world on tuesday at six pm today is World Water Day it\'s been observed annually since the United Nations started it in 1993 each year has a different theme around water in current world issues this year water and jobs and Samantha Weatherwax is in our nation\'s capitol talking to some Arizona leaders behind the initiative today is the United Nations World Water Day and experts from the desert came to DC to represent Arizona at the White House water summit earlier today we believe of course that safe clean water is worth the price Katherine Sorenson was one of the many water officials from around the country who traveled to Washington to raise awareness of water issues and to find potential solutions it\'s important for all of us to get together and in DC is a great place to do it and to have a place where we can all get together talk about the issues we\'re facing it see if there\'s innovative solutions that we can share not just across the aisle but also across the country Phoenix and Tucson were highlighted today for their conservation efforts as they are currently in a partnership which allows Phoenix to store water within Toussaint\'s infrastructure so by leveraging the infrastructure of both cities we gained tremendous efficiencies and really create resiliency for both communities Timothy Tom our director of tucson water services is happy with the progress that the partnership is made and is now looking towards the future we are looking at upwards of even close to forty thousand acre feet of water per year that could be stored in Tucson facilities which is about a third of Phoenix\'s allocation forty thousand acre feet is equivalent to a little over 13 billion gallons the more we can come together and work on these issues collaboratively hey that\'s a win-win for everybody other cities in the valley are gaining interest in the Phoenix Tucson partnership which could lead to even greater conservation efforts for Arizona reporting from the White House Samantha Weatherwax Cronkite news there has been a drought in the state of Arizona since 1999 and california state of see with water has the southwest asking how do we do more with less James Ulrich spoke to Arizona officials about what solutions they have for the water shortage the grass here at civic a civic space park is green but that\'s not due to any rain according to the National Weather Service we haven\'t had significant rainfall since februari first this in the valley this is a big concern for Arizona\'s political and business leaders who met today at the arrows at the business water summit in Phoenix when it comes to water shortage in the southwestern United States Senator Jeff Flake doesn\'t want the federal government to get involved we\'re going to have to find offsets it\'s going to involve a lot of negotiating and a lot of serious legislating so just saying that that\'s not an easy fix the days where you could simply rely on the federal government to make massive investments and our long past not everyone agrees with this the Public Policy Institute of California conducted a study last month and formed a policy recommendation in response to the Western drought Ellen henick the center\'s director said the government needs to use their power to help the numerous agencies cooperate over two dozen federal agencies are involved in Western water in one way or another leveraging that authority to really help push state and local partners to come to solutions in in basins where there are some tough challenges the Colorado River Basin forecast center estimates that there\'s a sixty percent chance that Lake Mead will suffer a water shortage by 2018 if this happens there would be an automatic water restriction in Arizona and Nevada and it may be the only circumstance in which flake will support federal government involvement it\'s been postponed because of better rains last year but but it\'s likely going to come as far as new new initiatives or new legislation by I don\'t foresee that I think it can be solved for the most part of the local level there are handful of bills going through the California and Arizona legislators one of these bills SB 1268 was rejected by the Arizona State House of Representatives Cochise County try to impose in a short plan of a 100-year water supply for potential developers in Phoenix James Ulrich Cronkite news some northern Arizona officials are taking another fight to Washington this time over Mojave counties out of control Butera population Cronkite news reporter Katie Bieri found out how federal law has protected these animals maybe a little too well they\'re cute slow-moving and apparently harmless but as the wild burro population has exploded they have taken a toll on resources and threatened Arizona motorists nobody has died yet but they\'re going to that\'s exactly what brought local county officials to Washington this week they met with federal officials and Senator John McCain to talk solutions to the problem if we\'re talking about it then we know about it and then it\'s on our hands right now the boro population sits at more than 4,400 that\'s three times more than our environment can sustain killing the burrows isn\'t an option because it\'s illegal but in a moment of frustration one officials suggested such a step I don\'t want to shoot the burrows nobody does but it takes that sort of rhetoric to get attention sometimes from the outlying areas Ma said he was glad to start a conversation but that long term there needs to be a better solution it\'s basically the Dutch boy putting his finger in the dam and hoping he can stop it from bursting but it\'s a start it\'s a band-aid but it\'s a start in Washington Katie Bieri Cronkite news 3d printing has opened a world of possibilities they\'re being used in schools and businesses across Arizona however reporter ben Brown tells us how it might also damage your health these aren\'t minor health problems we\'re talking about either a recent study shows that certain plastics used in 3d printing release emissions that could lead to cancer heart problems and other serious issues local motors and arizona-based manufacturing company works with 3d printers daily even building a 3d printed car 3d printing allows us to do something we\'ve never done in the past which is build something quickly and then grind it up recycle it and do it again and again and again but like with all new technology complications tend to surface and this one could have serious health implications the problem comes with the process so you\'re taking plastic you\'re melting it extruding it out a little nozzle and it just builds up one layer at a time that melting process can emit toxins a study conducted by researchers from the illinois institute of technology and other universities found that certain plastics such as abs can emit human carcinogens we\'ve actually had the hygienists come in and validate that what we smell is not a toxic chemical but it\'s it\'s like a perfume the hard part is for a home use you don\'t have that advantage and that as another concern for 3d printers becoming more affordable it\'s common to find them in homes or schools but despite the study Reiher says he wouldn\'t shy away from 3d printers honestly I don\'t think I would caution anybody from buying a 3d printer the key is understanding what you\'re doing according to researchers there is no evidence to suggest a design or make of a printer plays a factor so whether it\'s a large manufacturing 3d printer or a small one used at home caution should be used when 3d printing the study\'s authors also found nylon filament releases a toxin that can cause neurologic stomach in heart conditions and one way to limit these toxic emissions is to use biodegradable PLA plastic bin Brown Cronkite news Arizona is dealing with an overpopulation of desert tortoises but you can help Cronkite news reporter James Ulrich explains why the Arizona Game and Fish Department is asking residents to come out of their shell and adopt one tortoises here in the Phoenix area have been breeding a lot for the last century and so there\'s lots and lots of people with pet tortoises that are producing more and more baby tortoises and now there\'s really an overpopulation problem last year there were only 55 tortoises in the adoption center at this time this year that number has increased by more than 30 this guy here is tank he\'s from Kingman Arizona he\'s one of the 86 tortoises here the adoption center aside from the appearance there are several traits that make a tortoise different from a regular house pet some to say that they actually recognize individual people\'s voices they\'ll come in dog doors they learn that that\'s where the food is and they\'ll come in there they have these really human-looking eyes and they seem to kind of be wiser than we then we give them credit for potential owners must have an outdoor space for the tortoise as well as food and water but the registration that\'s the easy part it\'s actually free so you don\'t have to buy one they the ones that come through us on Adoption Day are microchipped already and given a number you just give him a name the tortoises grow to be about 15 pounds but can live for 50 to 100 years so plan on many years with this pet in Phoenix I\'m James Ulrich Cronkite news adoption day for these tortoises is april 9th to apply for adoption visit the Arizona Game and Fish Department\'s website to fill out the form the arizona game and fish department is taking care of an orphan mountain lion kidding Elena Mendoza tells us how she was rescued the mountain lion kitten was trapped in a tree alone and hungry I went to north phoenix today where the kitten is being rehabilitated her condition is was as bad as I\'ve seen maybe a little bit worse Arizona Game and Fish say they received a call yesterday from Animal Control in cells Arizona about a baby mountain lion trapped in a tree her sibling didn\'t make it found at the bottom of that same tree could been several days very likely with several days that she was away from her mom justice Allen says she suspects the mother also died because she would have brought her kitten down so normally we would we wouldn\'t interfere with with kittens in this case we could tell from the weight of the kitten that we found that we was trapped that the mother was not in the picture Arizona Game and Fish officials say the mountain lion kitten is about this big and weighs only 15 pounds when she should weigh about 30 pounds at the age of five to six months they estimate this kitten would have died without intervention the results of her bloodwork indicated that her emaciation and dehydration was significant but doesn\'t appear to cause any long-term damage to her body the good news is that she ate half a rabbit this morning so you know so those are the things are excited about we\'re gonna do what we can but just bringing a young animal young mammal in like this they very quickly get used to having people around them justice Allen says it\'s unclear at the moment if they will be able to release her back into the wild if and when she makes a full recovery Arizona Game and Fish advises anyone who sees a mountain lion kitten or any other baby wild animals to leave it alone in Phoenix Elena Mendoza Cronkite news that\'s it for Cronkite news tonight we are proud to be the news division of Arizona PBS for top arizona stories any time go to cronkitenews.azpbs.org for only the third time in the awards 74-year history a phoenix-based news operation wins the prestigious Alfred I DuPont Columbia Award for Excellence in broadcast journalism and this year that news operation is Cronkite news the news division of Arizona PBS honored for its work on the groundbreaking documentary hooked tracking heroin\'s hold on Arizona Cronkite news at Arizona PBS award-winning journalism you can count on from the station you trust when I was 12 years old I was watching great performances on PBS this program with Nureyev came on Nureyev in a performance of liquor ser and I was amazed and austra more I really wanted to to do it I was street dancing at the time and I never thought of formal dance until I saw great performances I knew that I was really a novice to dance like High dance I decided to check out the high school performing arts and so one thing led to the next today as a recognized dancer I absolutely believe that when i saw the performance it affected me tremendously and I know that\'s what happens when I teach I\'m opening an option for them that they hadn\'t seen before you\'re dreaming don\'t hi don\'t reason you', 'Watch how elementary students are using coffee grounds to support a community garden, how organizers of sporting events are saving water and how to succeed in competitive tree climbing.', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sustainability-beat-bring-you-stories-of-arizona-water-conservation-recycling-efforts-energy-innovations-and-new-initiatives-to-protect-the-environment-2', '', '', '2018-11-21 07:14:53', '2018-11-21 07:14:53', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=44', 0, 'post', '', 0);
