th several days that she was away from her mom justice Allen says she suspects the mother also died because she would have brought her kitten down so normally we would we wouldn\'t interfere with with kittens in this case we could tell from the weight of the kitten that we found that we was trapped that the mother was not in the picture Arizona Game and Fish officials say the mountain lion kitten is about this big and weighs only 15 pounds when she should weigh about 30 pounds at the age of five to six months they estimate this kitten would have died without intervention the results of her bloodwork indicated that her emaciation and dehydration was significant but doesn\'t appear to cause any long-term damage to her body the good news is that she ate half a rabbit this morning so you know so those are the things are excited about we\'re gonna do what we can but just bringing a young animal young mammal in like this they very quickly get used to having people around them justice Allen says it\'s unclear at the moment if they will be able to release her back into the wild if and when she makes a full recovery Arizona Game and Fish advises anyone who sees a mountain lion kitten or any other baby wild animals to leave it alone in Phoenix Elena Mendoza Cronkite news that\'s it for Cronkite news tonight we are proud to be the news division of Arizona PBS for top arizona stories any time go to cronkitenews.azpbs.org for only the third time in the awards 74-year history a phoenix-based news operation wins the prestigious Alfred I DuPont Columbia Award for Excellence in broadcast journalism and this year that news operation is Cronkite news the news division of Arizona PBS honored for its work on the groundbreaking documentary hooked tracking heroin\'s hold on Arizona Cronkite news at Arizona PBS award-winning journalism you can count on from the station you trust when I was 12 years old I was watching great performances on PBS this program with Nureyev came on Nureyev in a 