nually since the United Nations started it in 1993 each year has a different theme around water in current world issues this year water and jobs and Samantha Weatherwax is in our nation\'s capitol talking to some Arizona leaders behind the initiative today is the United Nations World Water Day and experts from the desert came to DC to represent Arizona at the White House water summit earlier today we believe of course that safe clean water is worth the price Katherine Sorenson was one of the many water officials from around the country who traveled to Washington to raise awareness of water issues and to find potential solutions it\'s important for all of us to get together and in DC is a great place to do it and to have a place where we can all get together talk about the issues we\'re facing it see if there\'s innovative solutions that we can share not just across the aisle but also across the country Phoenix and Tucson were highlighted today for their conservation efforts as they are currently in a partnership which allows Phoenix to store water within Toussaint\'s infrastructure so by leveraging the infrastructure of both cities we gained tremendous efficiencies and really create resiliency for both communities Timothy Tom our director of tucson water services is happy with the progress that the partnership is made and is now looking towards the future we are looking at upwards of even close to forty thousand acre feet of water per year that could be stored in Tucson facilities which is about a third of Phoenix\'s allocation forty thousand acre feet is equivalent to a little over 13 billion gallons the more we can come together and work on these issues collaboratively hey that\'s a win-win for everybody other cities in the valley are gaining interest in the Phoenix Tucson partnership which could lead to even greater conservation efforts for Arizona reporting from the White House Samantha Weatherwax Cronkite news there has been a drought in the state of Arizona since 1999 and california state of see with water has the southwest asking how do we do more with less James Ulrich spoke to Arizona officials about what solutions they have for the water shortage the grass here at civic a civic space park is green but that\'s not due to any rain according to the National Weather Service we haven\'t had significant rainfall since februari first this in the valley this is a big concern for Arizona\'s political and business leaders who met today at the arrows at the business water summit in Phoenix when it comes to water shortage in the southwestern United States Senator Jeff Flake doesn\'t want the federal government to get involved we\'re going to have to find offsets it\'s going to involve a lot of negotiating and a lot of serious legislating so just saying that that\'s not an easy fix the days where you could simply rely on the federal government to make massive investments and our long past not everyone agrees with this the Public Policy Institute of California conducted a study last month and formed a policy recommendation in response to the Western drought Ellen henick the center\'s director said the government needs to use their power to help the numerous agencies cooperate over two dozen federal agencies are involved in Western water in one way or another leveraging that authority to really help push state and local partners to come to solutions in in basins where there are some tough challenges the Colorado River Basin forecast center estimates that there\'s a sixty percent chance that Lake Mead will suffer a water shortage by 2018 if this happens there would be an automatic water restriction in Arizona and Nevada and it may be the only circumstance in which flake will support federal government involvement it\'s been postponed because of better rains last year but but it\'s likely going to come as far as new new initiatives or new legislation by I don\'t foresee that I think it can be solved for the most part of the local lev