(63, 1, '2018-11-21 07:26:04', '2018-11-21 07:26:04', 'on this edition of inside education during this statewide week of respect get ready for a culture shock we learn choreography we learn how to respect others and ourselves and how to be a good person we go inside a local nonprofit that teaches self-worth dignity and respect for all people through the power of dance then a big national honor for a local CCSD elementary school from the US Department of Education why Goolsbee Elementary has been named a national Blue Ribbon School plus what it takes to be a National Merit Scholar more than four dozen CCSD students are semi-finalists those stories and more inside education starts right now the cornerstone of education is getting to know a student first we want to make sure that we\'re supporting families and students [Music] thanks so much for joining us for this edition of inside education I\'m your host Mitch Truswell the first week of October is known in Nevada as the week of respect at its core week of respect is an anti-bullying effort and a time to celebrate diversity to remind students parents educators and the entire community that we all play a role in creating and maintaining a safe and respectful learning environment that\'s a year-long effort the Clark County School District\'s has adopted the theme be an upstander here\'s a snippet of a video by superintendent dr. hey Seuss Jarrah that helped kick off the week one emphasis of the week of respect is to be an upstander which encourages students to stand up and take an active role against bullying CCSD and the Clark County community get your blue on show each other respect and kindness now and throughout the entire year creating a respectful environment is also a primary focus for a local dance troupe they call themselves culture shock as inside education zku thetop is here to tell us the group\'s goal is to work with kids who love hip-hop and urban dance while also inspiring positive change and attitudes Kathy Mitch as soon as you walk into culture shock the dance studio you see the nonprofit\'s mantra on the walls and on t-shirts self-worth dignity and respect for all people they are not just words for members of culture shock it\'s a way of life five six seven eight go one this is culture shock dance we talk the relay a non-profit dance troupe committed to creative choreography culture shock is an organization that is dedicated to providing youth an opportunity to have a creative outlet as well as something else we cultivate self-worth dignity respect through dance so we try to take the children in the community and teach them life lessons an experience by using dance Judea Russell says once you join culture shock you never really leave janilla grew up in the troupe and now as an adult she\'s a professional dancer and her eight-year-old daughter naomi is learning the same steps and same life lessons that her mom did it\'s cold place where you learn to be respectful and to not be rude to others I know it sounds cliche that the children are our future but it but it is I started when I was a teen and now being an adult my daughter is now on the truth and in the program and it\'s it\'s very rewarding to now teach her all the things that I\'ve learned and the things that I didn\'t learn ways to be better in certain areas because now I\'m responsible for her confidence and self-worth and mmin having integrity and what she does family culture shocks executive director Evangeline vez kara Golda is a retired CCSD teacher who has seen firsthand the difference this dance troupe can make when they come in here they\'re all what so that\'s one thing we\'re very proud of our family is there everybody treats everybody the same way there\'s a very diverse group of kids a very diverse group of teachers diverse group of people families but when they all come in here we\'ll all have something in common and it\'s just the love the love of the family students often gather in the lobby to work on homework or simply talk outside of dance like if I have trouble with school like all right let\'s get together we\'ll figure this out like even for the kids like they\'re able to bring their schoolwork here and we\'ll like help them figure out like what they need help them get their grades up so it\'s just it just goes beyond just dancing still it is the love of expression that brings this group together it\'s its own language in a way it connects not only people that speak Spanish or English it can connect everyone and between the beats the moves the steps and the smiles these kids are building character gaining acceptance and respect we\'re teaching life skills we\'re teaching self-worth dignity respect for all people that\'s something that we wear proudly on our t-shirts because that\'s something that\'s really important to us and that we\'re happy to promote we\'re teaching them how to be not just great dancers but great people because ultimately that\'s what you want to create is better people here in the world culture shock Las Vegas is part of a network of culture shock organizations around the United States and Canada you can learn more about the local nonprofit and classes by going to its website which is on the bottom of your screen back to image Kathy thank you for that story the Clark County School District is acknowledging the contributions of the Hispanic community and culture during Hispanic Heritage Month beginning September 15th many schools in the district held special celebrations and events to honor the presence of Hispanic Latino culture in Southern Nevada including this event and Rancho high school organized by the Hispanic Student Union another event held at Northwest Career and Technical Academy included the sunrise Mountain High School Ballet Folklorico dancers Hispanic Heritage Month will end on October 15th one CCSD elementary school recently joined a pretty elite group Judy and John el Goolsbee elementary school was named a national Blue Ribbon School recently so how selective is this award Goolsbee is the only school to receive this award in the Clark County School District this year it is one of just three schools statewide to be named a Blue Ribbon School and one of just 349 schools nationwide to receive this recognition the award is based on overall academic excellence or progress in closing achievement gaps among student subgroups vice president of the school board of trustees Carolyn Edwards says what Goolsbee has done can be done at any school Tim Cunningham here at Goolsbee has done an exceptional job but it is the whole team if you don\'t have a team working together you can\'t accomplish this so this is really a great honor for this school but any school can do this and joining me now in studio is the principle of Goolsbee elementary school Kim Cunningham first of all we\'ve got to say congratulations this is a huge honor tell me how this feels for you and your team it\'s it\'s surreal we are so excited we\'ve been thinking about this for I\'ve been since last March we put the application in waiting to see if we would get it and found out on Monday that we got it how does that notification come through on Monday they sent us an email and said about I believe it came about 10 o\'clock and said congratulations you are a winner of the blue ribbon and then they gave us a website to look at and they had the US Secretary of Education talking and they have highlighted profiles for us and everything it\'s really exciting that\'s very exciting one thing I want to point out is you were you actually let\'s go back to ghouls be you I think got the highest scores for reading and and the high scores in math in the state last year any school last year that\'s what prompted the state to say we\'re gonna nominate you Google speech that\'s how yes okay Wow well I think probably a lot of people have the question at other schools besides congratulations it\'s like wow how do you do that there\'s a 