tion and also a resume with the extracurricular activities that you\'ve done throughout high school okay so you\'re the process of filling that out yeah and that will go into the running to see whether you\'re a finalist what\'s the toughest part is it the essay yeah it\'s definitely it\'s definitely the essence why is that so tough well the other parts the application are fairly straightforward like a resume and activities and stuff but the essay is where you really get to show who you are as an applicant and the application readers want to know about things like what\'s your motivation to learn or what experiences you\'ve had or really just anything that makes you unique and sitting there thinking how can I portray myself in a seven hundred word essay that\'s extremely difficult and it becomes a long process of drafting writing editing and peer review until you end up with essay that can really embody who you are and being able to read the essay and kind of see yourself in it is really satisfying but the whole process that I say writing definitely takes a while oh my gosh there\'s a lot of writing on that essay I think is what you\'re trying to say right so 19 dr. gehler 19 CCSD schools are represented with Merit Scholars five semi-finalists however one school Clark high school had I think probably I don\'t know of 75 25 or 25 students what do we say about that amazing absolutely amazing we have incredible talent and we\'re just incredibly proud of the students leadership at Clark high school I\'ve been there I\'ve walked classrooms I\'ve spent time with the leader and I could tell you takes great leadership and teachers to provide access and opportunity for these students to excel these students are very bright and very talented but providing those opportunities so they can have rigorous courses and have choices there so they can seek their path and and shine and and show the whole rest of the country what they know and what they\'re capable of what do you say about this school there\'s something going on - Clark what is it the environment yeah it\'s just like Clark is just kind of an environment that\'s really set up for academic success the students are all extremely driven to learn we have some of the most rigorous gorgeous of courses in the country and we have teachers who are really passionate about what they teach and always willing to help out the students and we also have a staff and administration that\'s always setting up setting us up for success they\'re always willing to help and they\'re always providing us with opportunities to pursue what everybody want to go into after high school that\'s great before we go I want to find out what what are your plans obviously to go to college but you have a field of study and you have a dream job well right now I really like entrepreneurship and I also really like studying math and science so ideally I would like to become an entrepreneur who uses math and science to create disruptive technologies I\'ve done a little bit of both I\'ve done some entrepreneurship with patenting and development and I\'ve also done some research at places like Stony Brook University and the National Institutes of Health and I really really love doing both so I like to mix the two together as for college I don\'t really have a specific place right now I\'m in the middle of the process you have some time you have some time but I just want to go to a good school that will allow me to pursue an education in mathematics and computer science I think you\'re gonna find it Aaron we wish you the absolute most success we can congratulations again dr. gullet thanks for joining us today my pleasure well finally we want to pass along a well-earned congratulations Clark high school Zeeshan Vakeel did very well during the 3rd international history Olympiad held in Berlin Germany recently the kil competed against 224 students representing 20 different countries including 20 different US states and came away with 3 gold to silver and 5 bronze medals the collection of medals helped Deshawn compile one of the most outstanding performances of any student at the competition he earned gold medals in the art history be a quiz tournament on the period of colonization in Africa as well as the history of the Berlin exam big congratulations to Ishaan the kill and we want to thank you for tuning in to insideeducation whether you\'re a student parent staff member or tax payer we all have a stake in the public education system a quick reminder that you can find this episode and past episodes of inside education on the Vegas PBS website that\'s Vegas PBS Oh RG or the Vegas PBS YouTube page as promised we\'ll be back in two weeks with more stories and interviews that take you inside the Clark County School District and we leave you now with the names of all those shining star schools congratulations to them we\'ll see you soon you', 'CCSD and other celebrate Week of Respect, and we look at school and student achievement.', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '61-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-11-21 07:26:04', '2018-11-21 07:26:04', '', 61, 'http://localhost/wordpress/63/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(64, 1, '2018-11-21 07:29:38', '2018-11-21 07:29:38', 'thank you for MC this year\'s superintendent Mary Randall from the bloomer school district and of course to the honor guard from vogue field for their part in our ceremony and how about those Beloit Memorial jazz orchestra musicians their outstanding I was lucky enough to visit them this last school year during fine arts month and I knew we are in a treat we were in for a treat today so director Chris parents thank you again for bringing your group here today I also like to recognize some really special guests that are with us today are three of our Supreme Court justices Shirley Abrahamson and Walsh Bradley and patience Roggensack all our legislators and the school board members and elected officials who are with us today I thank you for your continued support for our kids and our schools special round of thanks to our leaders of our state\'s educational organizations we have woody we\'d have from Oz bo ja schrader representing us aww Arlene Braden from react Gary Myra from wks John Ashley from the WA SB and of course was the executive director John John bales and all the members of our school district administrators who are here for their annual conference thank you all for your leadership I also value input from our local communities and I\'d like to recognize the hundreds of Wisconsin citizens that serve on what at at least on one of our 30 councils that provide advice and support to the to the Department of Public Instruction some of you are here today and I we are stronger because of your willingness to serve in these roles finally I want to thank my friend Jonathan over B who is here absolutely because of his talent but also in large part due to the personal request of my wife Cathy da doctor over B thanks today I\'d like to start out by talking about some of the exciting things that are happening in our schools and difficult challenges that we face lately I\'ve been thinking about this year\'s kindergarten class um because my granddaughter Kendall here today kindergartner and lapham school here in Madison I spend a lot of time thinking about what kindergarteners across the state will need to succeed the challenges their teachers will face and of course who\'s going to pay for it and how much some of you may know this but Kathy and I first met in kindergarten Plymouth Wisconsin we were in miss Potter\'s class while Cathy remains a constant in my life I will tell you that things and education ovulates obviously has changed the layout of our classrooms how we approach teaching our schools and public libraries even our class our playgrounds look different in the midst of all this change our state has obviously become more diverse growing up as a small town kid the first time I met someone who wasn\'t white was when I was working on a summer job and a canning factory just down the road from my home I think that my story may be similar to many Wisconsin nights my age and while this may seem like a recollection from a bygone era there are still places where this story could be pulled true today so what\'s changed and what\'s remain the same in most cat classrooms across the state the kindergarteners who showed up and Kendall\'s classroom as well as others showed up and our learning great things already but they\'re more diverse in all kinds of ways they come to schools with different life experiences and different needs I believe the opportunity for each and every child to excel especially our kids of color is one of the great moral issues of our day to succeed we need honest talk about the shared benefit of a system that promotes excellence for all I spread some I spent some time this summer with educational leaders who are around the country talking about equity and one of the things I took from this work is that while Wisconsin\'s achievement gaps are large we\'re not unique what did inspire me though was the honesty of my peers and the urgency that they have to address the root causes of inequity they did not shy away from courageous conversations and and yet they were also incredibly hopeful that this will be an era that improves the lives of color all across the united states and frankly you can\'t afford to lose that momentum our state and our nation does not leave this walls kindergarteners a problem that our today\'s leaders and all of us fail to recognize equity cannot be a discussion about improving the lives of some other kids some other kids from other parents if we see this as an issue of one school district or one school building we all fail this is about ensuring the prosperity of the next generation the students no matter their race no matter whether they have a disability and no matter who they love each and every one of them deserves our as a white guy from Plymouth I know this can be uncomfortable at times believe me there are growing pains but much like building relationships is absolutely crucial to helping kindergartner succeed the same holds true for solving adult issues it\'s hard to have honest conversations without getting defensive but i\'m pretty sure folks of color denton based din\'t invent racism women didn\'t ask for sexism gay kids did not create homophobia and babies are not born bigots those powerful and insistent carriers won\'t go away unless we take tackle them together you\'ve been in a school recently you saw that our educators are working to make sure each student meets his or her full potential and they recognize that each kid may need the extra lift to get there while I always say that every day that I visit a classroom is my favorite day one visit this last year really stuck out stuck to me i was on a high school fine arts visit in milwaukee talking with students about their work now you have to know and i know my wife Cathy noses I\'m not particularly artsy so I was absolutely out of my element in woodworking pottery graphics and design I saw a student with red hair and when I say red I mean it was red enough for me to walk walk up to her and ask her about her work her name was leslie and she came to the u.s. at the age of five and started school as an English Learner she\'s one of our immigrant students she navigated me through her portfolio explain how her art followed her through her life church journey both the good times and the bad times she talked about her the role her teachers played in her life she explained our art grew with her needless to say I was really impressed she then told me that she has she secured over ninety thousand dollars in scholarships to go to a university here in Wisconsin how about that she was so confident in describing her next steps that I knew I could push her a little bit I hope I found a nice way to say this to her but what I was thinking was what on earth are you gonna do with an arts degree she smiled and told me she was planning not to become an artist she is going to school for biology she told me the skills she learned as an artist perseverance rescission determination translate perfectly for the study of biology her school experience instilled in her the ability to persevere in any field so that while we talk about change in education one of a constant is a determination of our educators to serve kids like Leslie and kindergarteners across the state you\'ll find classroom led by people that give their hearts and souls to these kids day in and day out and you know what kindergarten teachers are like and thank goodness they do because when our students need that extra lift we need great educators more today than ever before but here\'s the question how long can we lean on educators to manage the change alone our state must take action to support our educators so that they can focus on helping every kid there are issues that we can no longer afford to ignore issues that are should not be left alone tackled by our educators alone to wit mental health supports for families and kids are stretched thin and frankly in many parts of the state are non-existent according to a recent center for disease control and prevention study up to one in five of Wisconsin kids as a mental health challenge one in five get this over half of our school-aged children face at least one identified form of adversity and these numbers cut across all demographics groups whether it\'s because mom lost her job or Paris the wars or any number of other traumas it means that half of Wisconsin 60,000 kindergarteners will need an extra lift to help them achieve their potential and educators will need help with that extra lift throughout our state I see schools working across sectors public and private to provide mental health services for our kids the state let\'s ratchet up its Flajnik financial commitments in this arena the community school model is another example of providing providing that extra lift these schools drive a child\'s success by removing barriers to learning by providing services like health care or extending building hours and facility use for families or coordinating job training and counseling skills students and their families together can reach full potential school as community community as school school nutrition programs can also provide that extra lift this year in superior I learned how critical a nutrition program is to helping kids achieve their one of the growing number of school districts that offer breakfast lunch and dinner to students and families the director of the program trains the staff to watch kid for kids faltering in the line on Monday morning because that may mean that kid did not eat that previous weekend and we cannot forget about the valuable role our libraries play all across the state school and public libraries are responding to the needs of children and families who need that extra lift not to be clear community schools libraries top-notch nutrition programs are not silver bolus in fact one of the things that keeps me up keeps me awake at night is wondering how far a system is stretched by changes without the proper support to remote excellence for every kid we cannot ignore the critical staffing shortages many of our districts face the most important factor to student success is access to a high quality teacher that was true 60 years ago when I was in kindergarten a long time ago but that also holds true today to put it simply not enough of our young people are considering careers in education as a member of the board of reasons I\'ve eaten lunch in my fair share of college cafeterias and if you want to talk change holy mackerel those places have changed as have the food has gotten a lot better but in my eight years of sitting shoulder-to-shoulder with college kids I\'ve never sat down to someone who has told me that they are pursuing a career in education not once now that\'s anecdotal bit of evidence here are some hard data graduation in enrollment in Wisconsin education programs is way down when compared to 2009 a cts surveys of test test takers indicates that fewer and fewer students are preferring education as a career and according to data collected from our district staffing survey districts are having a harder and harder time filling those high demand positions a special education bilingual education and career and technical education last month I begin begin efforts to help address those shortages through emergency rules designed to reduce hurdles for districts facing staffing issues these changes were identified by a group of administrators and teachers intent on making an impact without dumbing down the quality of the profession no matter what we do to remove barriers we still need the best and brightest and we cannot compromise on quality and that will not change either some of those changes may require us to engage policymakers to build long-term solutions but one strategy to send a positive message to our young people is absolutely free and we can do it today we need to end the negative rhetoric surrounding the teaching profession this is obvious no one becomes a teacher thinking they\'re going to become a millionaire that\'s that I firmly believe that educators across Wisconsin are under under compensated for the complexity and sheer weight of the work they do if you needed an example look no further than last year\'s national teacher the Wisconsin Teacher of the Year representative Roger King from home in high school let me tell you how Roger defines teacher Roger believes in parental and family involvement and he practices what he preaches he was his advisory committees made up of parents business folks and families to inform his teaching he pushes his students to investigate real-world problems his classes retooled or school green greenhouse to leverage a year-round growing cycle Roger is an FFA advisor a 4-h leader he coaches football and he serves as a co-chair for the La Crosse County interstate fair small animal barn committee I\'m not sure when Roger sleeps I\'m also convinced that Roger is not alone in his dedication to the job he\'s part and parcel of what we what we look at when we define teacher in Wisconsin he and our other Wisconsin educators deserve our thanks a round of applause teachers teach because they care about kids it\'s true back in my kindergarten classroom still true today and that however does not mean you should ignore the facts a recent study published by the economic policy institute show that us teachers had weekly wages so it\'s a direct comparison weekly wages that was seventeen percent lower than their college-educated peers well that statistic absolutely contributes to our staffing shortages it\'s a problem that\'s inherently tied to how we fund our schools from 2009 to 2014 Wisconsin ranked at the bottom for change and teacher paid according to the US census bureau a two point four percent decrease in take-home pay over six years the same stats show us among the lowest states for change and spending per student at just one percent change across those last five years we cannot afford to let that these trends continue the founders of our state crafted a system of public education and while they may not have ever pictured the candles classrooms of today they put great value on the idea of equitable of an equitable system last time our state\'s funding system was reviewed by Wisconsin Supreme Court the Court outlined three groups as key indicators of distress English language learners students with disabilities and students in poverty I worry that each year that we kicked the can down the road instead of addressing our funding problems we risk failing our obligation to all our kids and I know the public is with us as we around a need to address funding reform over the past five years passages of referenda have dramatically increased today almost eighty percent of school districts approve referendum citizens are voting to tax themselves because the state ain\'t pulling its weight no district should have to go to a referendum every 33 years to keep the doors open polling also confuses show that public the public favors more state funding for our schools but for every eight districts that can pass a referendum in today\'s environment there are two that can\'t this is already creating a system of haves and have-nots it\'s not acceptable it\'s not acceptable to my grandchildren sitting over there people around the state are taking notice it was two years ago and lead up to the budget cycle that I first began to notice grassroots Paris groups popping up all across Wisconsin a few weeks ago I gave some remarks at their second annual summit was floored by the number of additional groups that have organically formed around their communities and their owner kids I see some of them are in the audience today and I want to thank them for what they\'re doing to advance a bipartisan conversation around school funding thank you so much when i visit districts largest wall I see some really exciting things despite our challenges there is constant innovation and drive for excellence for all our kids from Fort Atkinson where a pond becomes a classroom to three lakes where the community works alongside their young people in a state-of-the-art Fab Lab from the student portfolios in West Salem and cutting and to the tots top-notch CTE programs in menomonie and nekoosa I could not be more prouder of the learning and innovation I see it\'s in large part because when I visit schools I meet people like Leslie the artists and future biologists since stories like Leslie\'s stories of kids growing and receiving the extra lift they need that illustrate the value our schools provide to the state if you dig deeper you\'ll find that her success was tied to a team of educators who helped her reach explore and grow without high-quality educators and staff those school buildings would be nothing but bricks so I want to close by asking something of each and every one of you and it\'s not small and it will not be easy but you\'re here because you care so you\'re clearly the right person to people to ask to help shoulder this burden we desperately need broad support to achieve excellence for each and every child we also need people who are willing to be honest people willing to talk to each other about inequities people willing to find strength and diversity that makes Wisconsin and America great you can do it and we can do this together I am convinced that if we speak up together with candor without fear solving our equity problems around school funding and school staffing will come it will come for every kid in Wisconsin we all at the kendall and a fellow kindergarteners across the state of Wisconsin to receive that extra lift to succeed I hope you\'ll join us and thank you so much for being here today you', 'State Superintendent Tony Evers delivers his 2016 State of Education Address in the Wisconsin Capitol Rotunda, Sept. 15, 2016.', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'state-superintendent-tony-evers-delivers-his-2016-state-of-education-address-in-the-wisconsin-capitol-rotunda-sept-15-2016', '', '', '2018-11-21 07:29:38', '2018-11-21 07:29:38', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=64', 0, 'post', '', 0),
