(88, 1, '2018-11-23 05:22:24', '2018-11-23 05:22:24', 'breaking news tonight hundreds of people missing unaccounted for as fires rage across California a painstaking search as a death toll continues to rise and tonight there\'s a new friend on the way chilling new murder charges two members of SEAL Team six and two US Marines charged with killing one of their own a Green Beret strangled in his sleep prominent Ivy League professors accused of sexually abusing their students the women at Dartmouth who say it was like a 21st century Animal House a stunning twist in the feel-good story of a couple who raised hundreds of thousands to help a homeless man in need they put out a story that hoodwinked an awful lot of people cops now say it was all a hoax and they were all in it together a new warning from the CDC be careful cooking that Thanksgiving dinner an outbreak linked to Turkey what every family should know the toy store where Tom Hanks friends found a piano about to open its doors again we\'ve got your first sneak peek inside and the moment that will bring you to this deputy\'s amazing gift you\'ve got to see this is NBC Nightly News with Lester Holt good evening to our viewers of the West where the full scope of the wildfire disaster is beginning to come into focus the death toll rising tonight to at least fifty nine and so many families hoping for word of loved ones as the search continues for the nearly three hundred people still missing President Trump now planning to travel to the area this weekend to visit with those impacted while some of the hardest hit could face a new threat from floods and mudslides NBC News national correspondent Miguel Almaguer is in the fire zone in Paradise California heartbreak search teams looking for nearly three hundred still missing victims who may have died in homes and cars as a wave of fire tore through here in this hard hit community filled with retirees many may not have been able to outrun the flames names and photos of the missing devastating stories it happened so fast I think that they they would have been in serious trouble in the hills outside Los Angeles also hit by wildfire they\'re already bracing for another disaster floods it\'s a silent killer there\'s not any warning she Brian Fennessy and his team took us above one of the many burn zones when fire burns in the hills it strips them of water absorbing brush and makes the soil hard during the storm all of that flows right into the sprawling massive communities below a month after wildfires raged near Montecito the mudslides that followed were ten times as deadly leaving far fewer rescued that there\'s a greater risk to life through these mud flows and there are actually two these wildland fires AC disaster many communities are living through tragedy everybody is struggling homes were those who escaped rebuilding their lives from the ruins as the search goes on for the missing Miguel Almaguer NBC News Los Angeles turning now for the fires of the west of the deadly nor\'easter blasting the eastern half of the country tonight millions impacted by an early season snowstorm dangerous conditions snarling roads power knocked out in places in schools shut down a wide path of misery from Missouri to New England our Ron Mott has the latest now from st. Louis winter came crashing into fall today harder wipeout right chronic across the country accidents and spinouts and disbelief over melting snow ice and sleet I don\'t like the weather from New York we\'re bridge commuters were at a standstill down to DC where the white house was blanketed in the Midwest snow in Chicago leading to slippery roads if the weather is bad always ask yourself is this trip necessary and in Cincinnati branches snapping under the weight of heavy ice here another crash here and a crash there and here\'s another one mr. powerlines again airports throughout the storm zone seen more than a thousand delays O\'Hare Atlanta Reagan National all contributing to a day of travel slowdowns the snow with this huge storm will last through the evening across New England it will last through the night eventually it\'ll turn to heavy rain overnight along the coast but inland areas where it stays as all snow they could pick up more than eight inches in st. Louis the Gateway Arch peek through a snowy Shield more than five inches falling the largest November pileup here in nearly 40 years it\'s already snowing like it\'s January that\'s pretty crazy I love it I\'m so excited I lived in the south my whole life so this is really the most snow I\'ve ever seen in my life here in st. Louis it\'s snow for the better part of 16 hours tomorrow though most if not all of this notion melt forecast high temperature in the mid 40s with plenty of sunshine but all in all a pretty potent first punch from winter lustre all right Ron Mott in st. Louis with winters early wake-up call Saudi officials today revealed the results of their investigation into the killing of journalist Jamal khashoggi saying five of eleven suspects could face the death penalty as questions grow over how much the Saudi Crown Prince knew about all this our chief foreign correspondent Richard Engel has more Saudi prosecutors alleged today when Washington Post columnist Jamal Khashoggi walked in to that Saudi consulate in Istanbul the Saudi agents waiting inside were only supposed to bring him back to Saudi Arabia that killing him was an on-the-spot decision that Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman knew nothing about I believe that an irrational thinking person will recognize that you sometimes things mistakes happen Saudi prosecutors will seek the death penalty for five of eleven suspects indicted for cushaw his murder but Turkey doubts the alleged Saudi hit team which reportedly brought a bonesaw with them just winged it multiple US officials have told NBC News the US intelligence community believes it\'s inconceivable the crown prince had no connection to the death while one mideast official tells us tonight the Saudi explanation is quote a great work of fiction but the question tonight will the Trump White House accept the Saudi explanation the State Department is calling it a good start but critics say this is just the accused hitmen becoming the fall guys lester richard engel tonight richard thank you felony murder charges have been filed against two elite Navy SEALs and two marine Raiders were allegedly strangling a Green Beret to death in Mali in 2017 NBC News Pentagon correspondent Hans Nichols now on the shocking crime Navy prosecutors say Staff Sergeant Logan Melgar was asleep when four fellow special operators burst into his locked room found him with duct tape and put him in a chokehold that killed him the mission in Mali was to train local forces to fight al-qaeda terrorists but they turned on their own the Navy accuses the two seals and the two marine Raiders of first driving to their house for the duct tape and then killing the 34 year old Green Beret while perpetrating a burglary initially Navy SEAL tonita Dolf claimed he and Melgar were wrestling and SEAL Adam Cranston Mathews joined in one of those SEALs told a witness that he choked him out to get back at Melgar for a perceived slight before are also accused of conspiracy and obstruction of justice for lying to investigators this type of behavior is unacceptable the larger special operation forces should not be judged by the actions of a few the accused faced the potential of life in prison Hans Nichols NBC News new developments tonight after the arrest of stormy Daniels lawyer Michael avenatti on suspicion of domestic violence avenatti defending himself and so is his most famous client Peter Alexander has the new details for us Peter what\'s the latest on all this hey Lester good evening two adult film star stormy Daniels is speaking out tonight about that domestic violence allegation against Michael avenatti saying that she will hire a new lawyer if it proves to be true Daniels calling the allegation very troubling but st. Americans should reserve judgment until the investigation is complete tonight there are still nose details about what allegedly happened it\'s still unclear who the alleged victim is Los Angeles police say a finale was arrested Wednesday suspected of felony domestic violence he\'s vigorously denied the allegation both his ex-wife and his estranged wife of rushed to his defense avenatti of course one of the president\'s most vocal antagonists today suggested on Twitter that the allegation is politically motivated Lester Peter Alexander at the White House Thanks there is late word this evening the Florida Senate race is headed to a manual recount the votes will now be counted by hand and procedure required by state law because of how close the margin is between Rick Scott and Bill Nelson tonight the FDA says it\'s taking drastic action to stop the spread of what it calls a national epidemic a skyrocketing number of teenagers who are vaping using e-cigarettes and the feds say they want to ban menthol cigarettes altogether we get more from NBC\'s Tom Costello in Boulder Colorado school nurse Liz Blackwell is on the frontlines of an exploding cigarette epidemic it\'s having an impact on whether or not they can participate in sports it\'s having an impact on their relationships within their families the problem is nationwide today the FDA said it\'s taking action what\'s at risk is that we\'re going to reverse the dramatic gains that we\'ve seen in recent years in terms of trying to bring down smoking rates among adults and among kids health experts say the fruity flavors in e-cigarettes target teens now the FDA is ordering stores that sell fruity e-cigarettes to physically wall them off from teens and verify every customer is at least 18 it\'s also moving to ban menthol cigarettes and flavored cigars the stats are alarming a stunning 78% increase in East cigarette use among high schoolers in just one year a 48 percent jump among middle schoolers the vaping industry says it supports raising the legal age to 21 but tonight the FDA is under fire for not banning flavored ecigs altogether while the tobacco industry insists it will fight the proposed ban on menthol cigarettes insisting they do not pose any greater health risk Tom Costello NBC News Washington Facebook is under fire again after a bombshell new report accuses the social media giant of not being forthcoming about the Russia misinformation campaign that played out on its platform during the 2016 election NBC\'s Jolene Kent now with more on that Facebook knew much more about Russian attempts to influence American voters in 2016 than it originally led on according to an explosive report in The New York Times the article saying CEO Mark Zuckerberg and deputy Sheryl Sandberg ignored warning signs and then sought to conceal them from public view NBC News confirming the social network hired an outside PR firm to deflect attention by spreading dozens of articles critical of competitors Google and Apple last night Facebook dropped the firm to suggest that we weren\'t interested in knowing the truth or that we wanted to hide what we knew or that we try to prevent investigations is simply untrue Facebook\'s board of directors said in a statement as a board we did indeed push Zuckerberg and Sandberg to move faster the big issue is that tech has had a very bad year led mostly by Facebook they were worried more about blame on themselves than they were about fixing the situation even Prince William today criticizing big tech all technology companies still have a great deal to learn about the responsibilities that come with a significant power this comes it\'s Facebook takes a financial hit the stock has dropped more than 20% in the last six months and the number of new users is slowing down as these scandals take a toll luster all right thank you joe laying Dartmouth College has been hit with a lawsuit were seventy million dollars from seven women who accused the school of ignoring their sexual misconduct complaints against professors for more than a decade now is our Gabe Gutierrez reports those accusers are speaking out Kristina rawan who just got her PhD in neuroscience at Dartmouth but in 2015 she says she was raped by one of her professors while attending a conference I\'ve no memory of that night we had sexual intercourse which I now believe to be a sexual assault she and six other women in a federal lawsuit filed this morning accused Dartmouth administrators of knowingly permitting three of its prominent and well-funded professor to turn a research department into a 21st century Animal House according to the class action complaint these professors leered at groped sexted intoxicated and even raped female students what Dartmouth did was too little too late in a written statement Dartmouth says it strongly disagrees with the lawsuits characterizations of the college\'s actions but as a result of the misconduct we found earlier this year by three faculty members we took unprecedented steps toward revoking their tenure and terminating their employment the biggest misstep of Dartmouth is not properly handling the complaints that have come forward in the early 2000s the New Hampshire Attorney General\'s Office has launched a criminal investigation into the allegations Gabe Gutierrez NBC News as millions and families get set to gather around the table for Thanksgiving a new warning from the CDC about an ongoing outbreak linked to Turkey NBC\'s Anne Thompson down what you need to know before cooking before these guys go from this to this a warning tonight about a salmonella outbreak linked to raw turkey ground meat patties and the birds themselves the CDC reports 164 people got sick in 35 states over the past year one person died the symptoms fever and stomach problems within 72 hours of eating to avoid getting sick experts say always cook your turkey to 165 degrees you can tell if your turkey is cooked thoroughly if you use a food thermometer and you have to measure the temperature of the inside of the bird at several different points thaw a frozen turkey in the fridge not on the counter and wash your hands before and after handling raw poultry to make sure your Thanksgiving is a happy one Anne Thompson NBC News New York tributes are pouring in tonight for Roy Clark the beloved country music legend who headlined the hit TV variety show kiha for nearly a quarter century many viewers also remember him as a frequent guest host for The Tonight Show with Johnny Carson Clark was 85 also tonight it was the feel-good story that made headlines and now authorities say it was all a hoax and just in times of the holidays our king gets the first look inside the iconic toy store making a big comeback and the moments moving so many to tears I\'ll tell you about it in inspiring America [Music] we\'re back now with a shocking twist and a heartwarming story that caught nationwide attention a couple raising hundreds of thousands of dollars for a homeless man in need people across the country pitching in money that authorities now say it was a scam here\'s NBC\'s Rehema Ellis when Johnny Bobbitt a homeless veteran reportedly gave his last 20 dollars to help a stranded cake McClure get gas last November she and her boyfriend Marc D\'Amico started a GoFundMe page to pay back his kindness the heartwarming story went viral and more than 400,000 dollars poured in 17 but now police say it was an elaborate hoax the trio cooked up together and tonight all three are charged with theft by deception and could face up to 10 years in prison I mean look they put out a story that hoodwinked an awful lot of people today the online reaction Swift and angry they used people\'s hearts to steal now someone who deserves help will not get it the prosecutor says the money was gone in a few months spent on a New Year\'s Eve Vegas trip a BMW luxury handbags casinos and cash withdrawals the feel-good story started to unravel a few months ago when Bobbitt sued - the couple claiming they kept most of the money back then they defended themselves and I still believe that we did a good thing another to forget tonight GoFundMe says this is a rare case of fraud and all 14,000 donors will get their money back Rehema Ellis NBC News coming up here tonight your first look at all the fun in store as an American icon makes a Tudor a good news about the pint-sized superhero who captivated the nation with a grand opening just in time for the holidays the famous toy store where Tom Hanks danced on the piano and big is about to open its doors again three years after closing in you\'ll never guess where gaudy shorts got a sneak peek inside you want to know what\'s better than toys under the Rockefeller Christmas tree how about an entire toy store [Music] welcome to FAO Schwartz making a Christmas comeback can I pull this please ooh for over a hundred and fifty years it captured the imagination of generations including a real princess and who could forget Tom Hanks in the movie big and that nostalgia can strike a powerful chord [Music] what\'s different this time around this store is so much more experiential I mean you can do everything from a kid grocery store to creating your own RC car at Bao\'s famous stuffed animals now sharing space with Hachem oles magic shows mad scientists 2,000 square feet of sweets a new era where women are toy soldiers to their costumes designed by supermodel Gigi Hadid good job Gigi a toy store hoping to remind us all to find a little time to play this isn\'t a toy museum have fun enjoy and on that note Ngati Schwartz News New York I think he may actually be down there still playing on that piano a happy update now about a boy we first told you about five years ago miles Scott aka batkid had the whole country cheering him on when his make-a-wish transforms San Francisco into Gotham City for a day remember this Myles was battling leukemia but now he\'s ten and we\'re pleased to report cancer-free a super hero indeed we\'ll take a short break that be back with the emotional life-changing moment that was all caught on camera [Music] in tonight\'s inspiring America the video that has moved so many of a sheriff\'s deputy for the first time in his life seeing the world in living color not your smallest implies that was a bit of an understatement Jeff Dishman has been color blind his whole life his colleagues at the Humboldt County Sheriff\'s Office had pitched in and bought him special glasses allowing him to see color for the very first time the gift the idea of deputy Samantha Freese who\'s worked with Dishman for eight years Dishman couldn\'t wait to share the news with his wife my wife and I saw my wife\'s eyes for the first time last night in there it\'s such a beautiful blue and my daughters are so beautiful a gift that brighten the day for so many of us - what an amazing moment and deputy Dishman says he can\'t wait to go back to the Grand Canyon and experience all of its colors for the first time that\'s nightly news for this Thursday I\'m Lester Holt for all of us at NBC News thank you for watching and good night hey NBC News viewers thanks for checking out our YouTube channel subscribe by clicking on that button down here and click on any of the videos over here to watch the latest interviews show', 'Early winter weather across the country causes accidents and commuter chaos, nearly 300 missing in Northern California Camp Fire, and colorblind correctional deputy sees color for first time.', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'early-winter-weather-across-the-country-causes-accidents-and-commuter-chaos-nearly-300-missing-in-northern-california-camp-fire-and-colorblind-correctional-deputy-sees-color-for-first-time', '', '', '2018-11-23 05:22:24', '2018-11-23 05:22:24', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=88', 0, 'post', '', 0),
